5. Application Specifications (How the system is built technically)
a. Architecture
The Sports Facility Booking System follows a three-tier architecture, which separates the system into three main layers:
Frontend (Presentation Layer):
 The frontend is responsible for the user interface and user interactions. It includes pages such as login/register, facility browsing, booking page, and admin dashboard. Users interact with the system through this layer.
Backend (Application Layer):
 The backend handles the business logic of the system. It processes user requests, manages booking logic (such as checking availability and preventing double bookings), handles authentication, and communicates with the database.
Database (Data Layer):
 The database stores all system data, including users, facilities, bookings, and payments. It ensures data consistency, integrity, and efficient retrieval.
The frontend sends requests to the backend via APIs. The backend processes the requests and interacts with the database, then sends responses back to the frontend.
b. Database Model
The system uses a relational database with the following main tables:
1. Users Table
user_id (Primary Key)
name
email (Unique)
password (Encrypted)
role (admin, user, staff)
2. Facilities Table
facility_id (Primary Key)
name
type (gym, football field, etc.)
location
description
price
3. Bookings Table
booking_id (Primary Key)
user_id (Foreign Key → Users)
facility_id (Foreign Key → Facilities)
date
time_slot
status (active, cancelled)
4. Payments Table 
payment_id (Primary Key)
booking_id (Foreign Key → Bookings)
amount
payment_status
Relationships
One user can have multiple bookings
One facility can have multiple bookings
Each booking belongs to one user and one facility
Each payment is linked to one booking
Constraints
Email must be unique
A booking must reference valid user and facility IDs
Double booking for the same time slot is not allowed 

